
1. What are widgets and why are they important in Streamlit?

Widgets are reactive UI controls (sliders, dropdowns, checkboxes) that capture user intent and trigger script re-execution with updated parameters. They transform static dashboards into interactive analytics platforms.

Engineering Value Proposition:

text
Static dashboard: Fixed charts → Limited insights
Interactive widgets: Dynamic filtering → Unlimited analysis paths
Time-to-insight: 45min (manual Excel) → 3sec (widget-driven)

Widget Categories by Function:

| Control Type | Purpose           | Examples                      |
| ------------ | ----------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Selection    | Discrete choices  | selectbox, radio, multiselect |
| Range        | Continuous values | slider, number_input          |
| Boolean      | On/off states     | checkbox                      |
| Text         | Free-form input   | text_input, text_area         |



2. When should you use slider instead of number_input?

Strategic control selection based on input domain and user mental model:

| Widget       | Optimal Use Case                  | UX Pattern             | Data Type                  |
| ------------ | --------------------------------- | ---------------------- | -------------------------- |
| slider       | Range scanning (parameter tuning) | Visual range selection | Continuous (0.1 precision) |
| number_input | Exact values (IDs, quantities)    | Keyboard entry         | Discrete (integer/float)   |

Implementation Decision Matrix:

python
# Parameter tuning (model hyperparameters)
learning_rate = st.slider("Learning Rate", 0.0001, 0.1, 0.001, 0.0001)
batch_size = st.slider("Batch Size", 16, 512, 64, 16)

# Exact quantities (business metrics)
target_revenue = st.number_input("Target Revenue ₹Cr", 10.0, 1000.0, 100.0, 0.1)
inventory_count = st.number_input("Stock Quantity", 0, 10000, 100, 1)

Performance: Slider → Visual intuition (drag-to-explore). Number_input → Precision entry.



3. How is radio different from selectbox?

radio: Expanded, always-visible options (≤6 items). selectbox: Compact dropdown (≥7 items).

| Widget    | Visual Design               | Optimal N Options | Use Case           |
| --------- | --------------------------- | ----------------- | ------------------ |
| radio     | Horizontal/vertical buttons | 2-6 options       | Primary navigation |
| selectbox | Collapsible dropdown        | 7+ options        | Secondary filters  |

python
# Primary page navigation (high visibility)
page = st.radio("Analysis Type", 
                ["Overview", "Revenue", "Customers", "Products"],
                horizontal=True, index=0)

# Secondary filters (space-efficient)
time_granularity = st.selectbox("Time Period", 
                               ["Daily", "Weekly", "Monthly", "Quarterly", "Yearly"])

Cognitive Load: Radio → Immediate scanning. Selectbox → Memory recall.



4. What does a checkbox return and how is it used in apps?

Checkboxes return boolean (True/False) representing toggle state persistence across re-runs:

python
# Toggle visibility
show_trendline = st.checkbox("Show trendline", value=True)
show_grid = st.checkbox("Grid lines", value=False)

# Mode switching
use_log_scale = st.checkbox("Log scale", value=False)
include_outliers = st.checkbox("Include outliers", value=False)

if show_trendline:
    fig.update_traces(line_shape="spline")

Production State Patterns:

python
# Persistent across sessions (st.session_state)
if 'advanced_mode' not in st.session_state:
    st.session_state.advanced_mode = False

st.session_state.advanced_mode = st.checkbox(
    "Advanced Mode", 
    value=st.session_state.advanced_mode
)

Return Value Lifecycle:

text
Initial render: default_value
User toggle:    inverted boolean
Next re-run:    persisted state



5. How do widgets help in data filtering and user interaction?

Widgets enable declarative data pipelines where user input → filtered dataset → visualization executes atomically:

python
# === FILTERING PIPELINE ===
with st.sidebar:
    # 1. Categorical filter
    region = st.multiselect("Region", 
                          df['region'].unique(),
                          default=df['region'].value_counts().head(3).index)
    
    # 2. Temporal range
    date_range = st.slider("Date Range", 
                          min_value=df['date'].min(),
                          max_value=df['date'].max(),
                          value=(df['date'].min(), df['date'].max()))
    
    # 3. Numeric thresholds  
    min_revenue = st.number_input("Min Revenue ₹L", 0.0, 1000.0, 0.0)
    
    # 4. Boolean toggles
    high_value_only = st.checkbox("High-value customers only")

# === REACTIVE FILTERING (vectorized) ===
filtered_df = df[
    (df['region'].isin(region)) &
    (df['date'].between(*date_range)) &
    (df['revenue'] >= min_revenue)
]

if high_value_only:
    filtered_df = filtered_df[filtered_df['lifetime_value'] > filtered_df['lifetime_value'].quantile(0.8)]

# === VISUALIZATION LAYER ===
col1, col2 = st.columns(2)
col1.metric("Filtered Records", len(filtered_df))
col2.metric("Revenue Filtered", f"₹{filtered_df['revenue'].sum():,.0f}")
st.dataframe(filtered_df.head(1000))

Pipeline Performance Characteristics:

text
Filter composition: O(n) boolean operations
Vectorized execution: 10-100ms for 1M rows
Real-time response: <500ms end-to-end
Cache hit rate: 95%+ with @st.cache_data


Production Widget Strategy Matrix

| Data Type         | Recommended Widget | Alternative     | Validation   |
| ----------------- | ------------------ | --------------- | ------------ |
| Categorical (10+) | multiselect        | selectbox       | isin() check |
| Categorical (≤6)  | radio              | selectbox       | == check     |
| Continuous range  | slider             | number_input ×2 | between()    |
| Discrete count    | number_input       | slider          | ≥0 integer   |
| Temporal          | date_input         | slider          | valid date   |
| Boolean           | checkbox           | toggle          | True/False   |


Advanced Interaction Patterns

python
# 1. Dependent widgets (cascading filters)
if region:
    subcategories = df[df['region'].isin(region)]['subcategory'].unique()
    subcategory = st.multiselect("Subcategory", subcategories)

# 2. Callback-driven (immediate response)
def update_preview():
    st.session_state.preview_price = st.session_state.price_slider

price_slider = st.slider("Price", key="price_slider", on_change=update_preview)

# 3. Bulk operations (form container)
with st.form("batch_filter"):
    batch_size = st.number_input("Batch Size")
    auto_approve = st.checkbox("Auto-approve")
    submitted = st.form_submit_button("Apply Filters")

